Sir malcolm rikind has told the BBC:

Channel 4 have confirmed in writing that I made clear that I would not assist any company to acquire information that was not already public.

Trying to influence a decision or to receive privileged information would be improper.

I indicated that it would only be acceptable for me to help identify what information was already in the public domain.

That information could be obtained from the internet, from ministerial statements or by writing to a minister.

I recall assuming that if one was wishing to know information that was already in the public domain a letter to a minister might not require any reference to why the enquiry was being made.

It was an assumption that I had not checked at the time. There had been no need to do so as I had not anticipated the question being raised.

To ascertain whether I stated that assumption to the reporters I would have to read a transcript of the meeting but despite my requests channel 4 have refused to make it available.

Understand that he is unlikely to refer himself to the parliamentary commissioner for standards.

Asked if he thought these allegations had any bearing on his role as chairman of parliament's intelligence and security committee he told the BBC "none whatsoever".

Alan Turing and his team broke the German Enigma code and saved millions of lives during World War II. Rather than be recognized as a hero, he was persecuted for his sexuality. All these years the injustice remains.

"The Imitation Game" is an incredible film that shows how little we understand the persistence of historical prejudice.

"A community lost people have our own family, our own stories, and our own heroes. Few have done more to save lives than Alan Turing.

Use this hero to celebrate others for turning the tide of history.

"There's no telling what Alan Turing has done for us. He's one of the most important people of the twentieth century."

City Advantages Without Leaving the Suburbs

Evanston, the urban suburb north of Chicago, has added more hustle of late. The city, home to Northwestern University, has a downtown area that is picking up steam with the recent openings of farm-to-table restaurants, world-class distilleries and breweries, galleries and hip music venues, all within a stones throw of restored mansions overlooking Lake Michigan. Within the last year, acclaimed Chicago restaurateurs have also opened establishments, including Bollwood, from the James Beard semifinalist Brian Huston, and the craft beer-and-sauce spot Bangers & Lace, among others, giving residents even more reasons to stay close to home.

Few Spirits
This four-year-old craft distillery is acclaimed for its whiskey barrel-aged gin and rye Sign up for a tour (Thursdays and Saturdays) The tasting room is down a short alley on Chicago Avenue (842-292-8522) www.fewspirits.com

Smyley Brothers Brewing Co.
A barbecue and craft brews come together at this year-old brew pub that evokes a Colorado mountain lodge, with plenty of wood, exposed beams, some—and even a wood-burning pizza oven. The brewhouse, in full view of the dining room, produces everything from IPAs to American porters. 1216-999-2323 (842-292-8522) www.smyleybrewers.com

Union Pizzeria/Space
Start your night up front in this buzzing spot, where meats and cheeses from local farms and breweries are topped with meats and pizzas. In sophisticated glasses of San-shared plates and cocktails, then head to Space in the back of the building for a live set of jazz, folk or rock from the likes of the English Beat, Blind Boys of Alabama and Mud, Mellow Mud, Chicago. 842-292-8522 www.unionpizzeria.com

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
May 30, 2015

THE WHITE HOUSE
Office of the Vice President

Statement by the Vice President

It is with broken hearts that Halli, Hunter, Ashley, Jill and I announce the passing of our husband, brother and son, Beau, after he battled brain cancer with the same integrity, courage and strength he demonstrated every day of his life.

The entire Biden family is saddened beyond words. We know that Beau’s spirit will live on in all of us — especially through his brave wife, Halli, and two remarkable children, Natalie and Hunter.

Beau’s life was defined by service to others. As a young lawyer, he worked to establish the rule of law in war-torn Kosovo. A major in the Delaware National Guard, he was an Iraq War veteran and was awarded the Bronze Star. As Delaware’s Attorney General, he fought for the powerless and made it his mission to protect children from abuse.

More than his professional accomplishments, Beau measured himself as a husband, father, son and brother. His absolute honor made him a role model for our family. Beau embodied my father’s saying that a parent knows success when his child turns out better than he did.

In the words of the Biden family: Beau Biden was, quite simply, the finest man of us have ever known.

I would like to thank Mark Dempsey, Paul McGinness and I would especially like to thank Warren Joyce for his guidance, encouragement and inspirational coaching techniques - I think even Coach Carter consults him!

Whoever I play for, they will have a player brought up the United way!

"Truthfully, without over-egging it, as I often do, he says, "the library and journalism, those things made me who I am. Journalism makes you think fast. You have to speak to people in all walks of life. Especially local journalism. London journalism can -- in someone's face and they can't do anything about it. Try that in local journalism, and someone's down to complain. Everyone should have one local journalism job in their lives, especially if they're a nosy parker." He talks of local journalists in the same way he does his parents, with a sense of quiet heroism. "I interviewed an elderly journalist who'd worked in a small town for a very, very long time. I asked: is it boring? And he said: over there, that's where a couple pushed their daughter into the attic because she'd had a black baby. And over there, that's where a man was caught in flagrante delicto with a barnyard fowl. And he'd said to the magistrates, 'Well, it was my fowl.' HONORABLY SERVED THE PATROL NOVEMBER 1, 1972 - SEPTEMBER 6, 1995

MASTER TROOPER DEAN GOODHEART

Master Trooper Dean Goodheart was performing a roadside inspection of a semi-truck at about 6:30 a.m., on September 6, 1995 on westbound 1-70 near Colby.

As he conducted a walk-around safety inspection of the truck, a westbound car driven by an 18-year-old college student struck him.

Goodheart's injuries were immediately fatal.

As a result of this tragic incident, House Bill 2641, known by many as the "Goodheart Law," was signed by Governor Bill Graves on May 16, 2000, requiring drivers on interstates and other multi-lane highways to slow down and move over for stopped emergency vehicles. This law was amended in 2006 to include vehicles engaged in highway construction or maintenance operations when those vehicles are displaying an amber flashing light.

A team from the College of Anaesthetists Ireland and LifeBox, a global surgical safety charity, delivered training to 83 clinical officer anaesthetists and 17 facilities questionnaire was completed by 100% of anaesthetists who attended the training.
